<p><b>Edmund Burke</b> (12 January 1729<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup>&#160;– 9 July 1797) was an Irish statesman, author, orator, <a href="/wiki/Political_theorist" title="Political theorist" class="mw-redirect">political theorist</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Philosophy" title="Philosophy">philosopher</a> who, after relocating to <a href="/wiki/England" title="England">England</a>, served for many years in the <a href="/wiki/British_House_of_Commons" title="British House of Commons" class="mw-redirect">British House of Commons</a> as a member of the <a href="/wiki/British_Whig_Party" title="British Whig Party" class="mw-redirect">Whig</a> party. He is mainly remembered for his opposition to the <a href="/wiki/French_Revolution" title="French Revolution">French Revolution</a>. It led to his becoming the leading figure within the <a href="/wiki/Conservatism" title="Conservatism">conservative</a> faction of the <a href="/wiki/British_Whig_Party" title="British Whig Party" class="mw-redirect">Whig party</a>, which he dubbed the "Old Whigs", in opposition to the pro-French-Revolution "New Whigs" led by <a href="/wiki/Charles_James_Fox" title="Charles James Fox">Charles James Fox</a>. He is generally viewed as the philosophical founder of modern <a href="/wiki/Conservatism" title="Conservatism">conservatism</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
